  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The Brisbane residential marketing mix used to be simple. A quality photography package, a signboard, well-written copy, and premium listings on realestate.com.au and domain.com.au covered close to 100 per cent of what a well-run campaign needed. That structure still anchors most campaigns today, but a newer layer has become increasingly common: paid social media advertising on Facebook and Instagram, and more recently on TikTok for certain buyer segments.</p>

      <p>The question many Brisbane sellers now face is whether to allocate part of the marketing budget to paid social, and if so, how much. The honest answer is that paid social pays off for some properties and is a distraction for others. Getting the judgement right on your specific property requires understanding what paid social actually delivers, what it does not deliver, and how the costs compare to the results it generates against the existing marketing baseline.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What paid social actually does</h2>
      <p>Paid Facebook and Instagram advertising places your property's photography and video in front of specific segments of the Meta platforms' Brisbane and interstate audiences. The targeting is based on factors including age, suburb of residence, estimated household income, Facebook activity that suggests property interest, and custom audiences built from past visitors to the agency's website.</p>

      <p>The platforms also support retargeting, which places additional ads in front of users who have already viewed the property's portal listing or landing page but did not inquire. Retargeting is often the most efficient paid social activity, because it is reaching buyers who have already demonstrated specific interest in the property rather than people who just happen to live nearby.</p>

      <p>Paid social is a video-first format. Instagram Reels, Facebook video posts, and short-form vertical video on both platforms consistently outperform static photography in terms of engagement and click-through to the listing. A good paid social campaign for a Brisbane property therefore usually requires video content in addition to standard listing photography, which has implications for both the production budget and the creative brief.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What paid social does not replace</h2>
      <p>Paid social is an add-on to the core marketing layer, not a substitute for it. A few points are worth stating clearly, because they get blurred in sales pitches from agencies offering social-heavy packages.</p>

      <p>Serious buyers still search on realestate.com.au and domain.com.au. The overwhelming majority of transacting Brisbane buyers, across every price bracket, use the major portals as their primary search tool. Buyers who are actively in the market have portal alerts set up for their target suburbs and price ranges. A property that is under-indexed on the portals cannot be compensated for by strong social advertising; the buyers are not on Facebook searching for homes.</p>

      <p>Paid social does not fix fundamental problems. A property that is overpriced, poorly presented, or inadequately photographed will not suddenly perform because it has been placed in front of more people via social advertising. If anything, social ads for a property with obvious issues accelerate negative word of mouth, because the property is now visible to a wider audience of people who can see the problems.</p>

      <p>Paid social does not generate qualified buyers for entry-level properties. Buyers in the under $900,000 Brisbane market are generally searching portals actively and efficiently; they do not need a Facebook ad to find a listing in their price range. Paid social advertising to generic Brisbane audiences for a sub-$900,000 home typically produces high impression counts and low inquiry rates.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When paid social pays off</h2>
      <p>Paid social campaigns deliver measurable value on a specific subset of Brisbane properties. The pattern is consistent across our experience and the results that well-run agencies report.</p>

      <p>Premium properties above approximately $2 million. At this price point, the potential buyer pool is narrower and less likely to be on portal alerts for every available listing. Paid social lets the campaign reach high-income Brisbane residents who may be in the market for a premium upgrade but are not actively searching. Retargeting works particularly well in this bracket because a smaller pool of serious buyers view the listing multiple times before deciding to inspect.</p>

      <p>Unique or lifestyle properties. Queenslander homes with strong visual character, architectural renovations, riverfront positions, acreage properties, and homes with distinctive features (a view, a garden, a pool, a period character) respond well to video-first paid social. The visual story sells the property and paid social is the best format for a visual story.</p>

      <p>Properties aimed at interstate buyers, relocators, or returning expats. Sydney, Melbourne, Perth, and Adelaide buyers considering a Brisbane move often are not on Brisbane portal alerts. Paid social targeting can surface a Brisbane listing to these audiences directly. Expats returning to Australia are a smaller but important segment where social targeting is often the only practical reach mechanism.</p>

      <p>Pre-launch awareness campaigns. For premium properties considering an off-market or pre-public launch, paid social can generate a warm audience of interested parties before the portal listing goes live. This allows the campaign to open with inspection bookings in hand rather than relying entirely on portal inquiry in the first week.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When paid social is typically a poor investment</h2>
      <p>The same pattern logic identifies the scenarios where paid social should not be the priority in the marketing budget.</p>

      <p>Standard properties in hot market segments. A well-presented three-bedroom home in Camp Hill, Morningside, or Carindale at a sensible price point already benefits from intense buyer attention via portal alerts. Adding paid social to a property that is already generating strong inspection numbers produces minimal incremental inquiry and consumes budget that would be better spent elsewhere.</p>

      <p>Budget-constrained campaigns. Marketing budgets on Brisbane sales are typically $3,500 to $8,000 for a standard campaign, rising to $15,000 or more for premium properties. Allocating $1,500 to $3,000 of a $5,000 budget to paid social routinely displaces spend that should be going to photography quality, video production, styling, or premium portal placement. The opportunity cost of a social ad buy is usually something else that would have driven more inspections.</p>

      <p>Properties with weak visual appeal. Paid social is a video-first format, and some properties simply do not perform well on video. Compact apartments, properties on busy roads, homes with challenging floor plans, or properties where the best features are functional rather than visual will not gain from social advertising. The money is better spent on strong written copy and portal positioning.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The cost structure in Brisbane</h2>
      <p>A reasonable paid social campaign for a premium Brisbane property typically runs $1,500 to $4,000 over three to four weeks, sitting on top of the standard portal and photography spend. The cost breaks down into three components.</p>

      <p>Ad spend on the Meta platforms, which is the actual cost of placement and impressions, usually accounts for 50 to 70 per cent of the total. The rate varies with the targeting specificity, the creative quality, and the current auction competition, but a daily spend of $60 to $150 is typical for a focused Brisbane campaign.</p>

      <p>Creative production, if video is not already part of the base marketing package, adds $500 to $1,500 for short-form vertical video suitable for Reels and TikTok. Using existing photography and standard video is cheaper but produces weaker results; investing in purpose-built vertical content materially improves the campaign.</p>

      <p>Campaign management, whether handled by the agency's in-house team or a specialist digital agency, adds $300 to $800 per campaign. This covers targeting configuration, creative uploads, performance monitoring, and weekly reporting. Self-managed campaigns are possible but rarely deliver the return a specialist can produce.</p>

      <p>A total paid social allocation above $5,000 is rare outside genuinely premium campaigns. A total allocation below $1,500 is usually too small to produce meaningful reach on a three-to-four week campaign. Budgets outside that $1,500 to $5,000 range are worth questioning.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who actually runs the campaigns</h2>
      <p>There are three common structures for who executes a paid social campaign on a Brisbane listing.</p>

      <p>The agency's in-house marketing team. Larger Brisbane agencies have in-house digital marketing staff who manage paid social as a standard service. The advantage is coordinated creative and consistent messaging across the campaign. The disadvantage is that most agency teams are generalists rather than social specialists, and performance varies.</p>

      <p>Specialist real estate digital marketing agencies. A handful of Brisbane agencies specialise specifically in real estate social advertising and are brought in as a subcontractor on premium campaigns. These specialists usually produce stronger creative and better targeting than general agency teams, at a higher cost per campaign. They are worth engaging for properties above the $2 million mark.</p>

      <p>The seller directly engaging a digital consultant. Some sellers, particularly those with marketing backgrounds, prefer to run their own paid social campaign in parallel with the agent's portal-focused marketing. This can work when the seller has the technical skills and time to execute, but requires coordination with the agent to avoid conflicting messaging.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The most common execution mistakes</h2>
      <p>Several mistakes recur in paid social campaigns for Brisbane property listings. Knowing them helps you assess whether a proposed campaign is worth your money.</p>

      <p>Boosting a portal listing URL without a dedicated landing page. Sending paid traffic to a realestate.com.au listing page wastes the opportunity to capture buyer contact details and to retarget. A dedicated campaign landing page on the agency website or a custom property site provides both a better user experience and the data infrastructure for retargeting.</p>

      <p>Using generic static text ads rather than high-quality video content. Static ads are dramatically outperformed by video on both Facebook and Instagram in the current algorithm environment. If the budget does not support video creative, the campaign is unlikely to produce strong results.</p>

      <p>Targeting too broadly. A Brisbane-wide targeting approach produces impressions on people who will never inspect the property. Narrowing targeting to specific suburbs, age brackets, and income profiles produces a smaller reach but higher conversion to inspections.</p>

      <p>Running short campaigns under two weeks. The Meta algorithms need a minimum of 10 to 14 days to optimise delivery for a campaign. Campaigns of one week or less rarely generate the engagement data required to optimise, and their cost per click or cost per inquiry is usually high.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to measure whether it worked</h2>
      <p>The wrong metrics are tempting but misleading. Likes, comments, and follower counts do not correlate with sale outcomes. The right metrics are those that track movement toward the actual sale.</p>

      <p>Landing page traffic and time on page indicate genuine buyer interest. A campaign producing 500 landing page visits with a median time of 45 seconds suggests real engagement; 5,000 visits with a median of 8 seconds suggests the targeting is off.</p>

      <p>Inspection bookings and qualified inquiries are the definitive metric. If the paid social campaign produces bookings and inquiries that would not otherwise have come via the portals, the spend is paying off. If inspection volumes are indistinguishable from what the portal campaign alone would have produced, the spend is not justified.</p>

      <p>Tracking infrastructure needs to be set up before the campaign launches. Conversion pixels on the landing page, lead form tracking, and UTM tagging on every ad link make post-campaign analysis straightforward. Without this infrastructure, the reporting is guesswork.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to ask your agent</h2>
      <p>If your agent is proposing paid social as part of the marketing package, five questions are worth asking before agreeing.</p>

      <p>Is paid social included in the base commission or added as a line item? Transparency on what you are actually paying for each element matters more than the headline number. If social is included in the package but is not working, you cannot redirect that spend.</p>

      <p>What specific targeting will be used? The agent should be able to describe the audience segments in concrete terms (suburbs, age ranges, interests, retargeting pools). Vague answers indicate a campaign that will not perform.</p>

      <p>What creative assets will be produced and who owns them? Video content produced for your campaign should ideally be yours at the end of the campaign, not the agency's permanent marketing asset.</p>

      <p>What metrics will be reported, and how often? Weekly reporting with landing page traffic, inspection bookings attributable to social, and cost per qualified inquiry is the minimum. Monthly or end-of-campaign-only reporting is inadequate.</p>

      <p>What would we do with this budget if we did not spend it on social? A strong answer indicates the agent has thought about opportunity cost. A weak answer indicates social is being added for its own sake rather than because the analysis supports it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>For standard Brisbane properties in well-established suburbs, a strong portal listing combined with professional photography and a well-written description drives the great majority of sale outcomes. Paid social is a premium add-on for properties where the buyer pool genuinely benefits from active reach: premium homes, unique properties, and campaigns aimed at interstate or expat audiences.</p>

      <p>For properties where paid social does make sense, a focused three-to-four week campaign with video creative, tight targeting, and proper measurement infrastructure produces the most reliable results. Expect to spend $2,000 to $5,000 on the full campaign and expect to see meaningful retargeting traffic, inspection bookings, and inquiry attribution if the work has been done properly.</p>

      <p>For every property where paid social is being proposed, the same question applies: would this budget produce more inspections if allocated differently? If the honest answer is no, proceed with paid social. If the honest answer is yes or unclear, spend the money on the marketing fundamentals instead.</p>

